│ Understanding the Issue\n\nThe crash occurs due to an assertion failure,                   │
│ `!areInvalidOperands(C, S1, S2)`, during the creation of a `select` instruction within the │
│ `instcombine` pass. This assertion ensures that the condition vector's element count       │
│ matches the element count of the true/false value vectors. The crash indicates that        │
│ `instcombine` is attempting to create a `select` instruction with mismatched vector        │
│ lengths.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe backtrace clearly shows the failure        │
│ happens within `visitShuffleVectorInst` when it calls `FoldOpIntoSelect`. The IR being     │
│ processed is:\n\n```llvm\n%sel = select <2 x i1> %cond, <2 x float> zeroinitializer, <2 x  │
│ float> splat (float 1.0)\n%shuf = shufflevector <2 x float> %sel, <2 x float>              │
│ zeroinitializer, <4 x i32> <i32 0, i32 1, i32 2, i32 3>\n```\n\nThe optimization attempts  │
│ to push the `shufflevector` operation (`%shuf`) into the `select` instruction (`%sel`).    │
│ The goal is to transform `shuffle(select(c, v1, v2), ...)` into `select(c, shuffle(v1,     │
│ ...), shuffle(v2, ...))`.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe core of the problem lies in │
│ the `FoldOpIntoSelect` utility function. This function is designed to sink an operation    │
│ through a `select`. In this specific case, it tries to create two new `shufflevector`      │
│ instructions, one for the \"true\" path and one for the \"false\" path of the original     │
│ `select`. It then plans to create a new `select` that uses the original condition to       │
│ choose between the results of these new shuffles.\n\nThe original `select` instruction,    │
│ `%sel`, has a condition of type `<2 x i1>`. The `shufflevector` instruction, `%shuf`,      │
│ produces a result of type `<4 x float>`. When `FoldOpIntoSelect` creates the new           │
│ `shufflevector` instructions for the true and false branches, these new shuffles correctly │
│ have the type `<4 x float>`.\n\nThe bug is that `FoldOpIntoSelect` then attempts to create │
│ a *new* `select` instruction using the *original* condition (`<2 x i1>`) with the results  │
│ of the new shuffles (`<4 x float>`). This violates the LLVM IR rule that a vector          │
│ `select`'s condition must have the same number of elements as its selectable operands. The │
│ code is trying to do `select <2 x i1> %cond, <4 x float> %new_shuf1, <4 x float>           │
│ %new_shuf2`, which is invalid and triggers the assertion.\n\nThe logic in                  │
│ `FoldOpIntoSelect` does not account for operations like `shufflevector` that can change    │
│ the vector length. It incorrectly assumes the new `select` will have the same dimensions   │
│ as the original one.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nTo fix this, we need to modify    │
│ `FoldOpIntoSelect` to check if the vector length of the new operands matches the vector    │
│ length of the original `select`'s condition. If they do not match, the transformation is   │
│ invalid and should be aborted.\n\nThe check should be added in                             │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstructionCombining.cpp` inside the                      │
│ `InstCombinerImpl::FoldOpIntoSelect` function, right before the new `select` instruction   │
│ is created.\n\n```cpp\n// llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstructionCombining.cpp\n\n//   │
│ ... inside InstCombinerImpl::FoldOpIntoSelect ...\n  Value *V1 =                           │
│ Builder.Create(Op.getOpcode(), {SI->getTrueValue(), Op.getOperand(1)});\n  Value *V2 =     │
│ Builder.Create(Op.getOpcode(), {SI->getFalseValue(), Op.getOperand(1)});\n// ...\n  //     │
│ Check that the type of the new select is compatible with the condition.\n  if              │
│ (V1->getType() != SI->getType())\n    return nullptr;\n\n  return                          │
│ SelectInst::Create(SI->getCondition(), V1, V2);\n```\n\nThis change ensures that we only   │
│ proceed with creating the new `select` if the types are compatible, preventing the         │
│ crash.\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nThe proposed fix correctly identifies and prevents an       │
│ invalid transformation within `instcombine`. By adding a type-compatibility check in       │
│ `FoldOpIntoSelect`, we ensure that length-changing operations like `shufflevector` do not  │
│ lead to the creation of malformed `select` instructions. This resolves the reported        │
│ assertion failure and makes the optimizer more robust."})                                  │
